logy. Fly your experiments.</h1>'),(247,'<div class=\"grid_8 alpha\"><p>Testing in a relevant environment.Objective of this page: describe the need/objective of OCT to mature technology. And the fact that this program was specifically set up to facilitate this mission of OCT. This program is part of a larger strategy of OCT to create a pipeline for technology maturation through all the different stages. From early concepts, through breadboarding, and eventually flight testing. This program is part of the last segment in the pipeline (show image of OCT pipeline).</p><p>So if you are interested in flight testing your technology, or you are still at a pre stage (2nd division), you will be interested to know this progam exists to pick up where you are leaving the other segment of the pipeline. The Program is also open for projects in the realm of science or \r\neducation. The Program has a growing list of platforms and environments on offer. Currently it covers parabolic flights and sRLV.<br />\r\n</p>\r\n<p>The Flight Opportunities Program has an increasing number of platforms available that span the range from parabolic aircraft (traditional, for zero-g) to sRLV platforms that will create access to an environment as of yet not reachable (the ignorosphere). Across all these platfroms, there is a wide range of possibilities and capabilities of interest to various customers. From the traditional Technology maturation where Zero-g might be a useful characteristic to test your technolgy, to science in unexplored regions. And education opportunities exist across the various regimes and platforms</p><p>The payloads may be exposed to a near-zero or reduced gravity\r\nenvironment by flying on aircraft that provide parabolic flight trajectories\r\nand on suborbital reusable launch vehicles (sRLVs) that are potentially capable\r\nof flying to altitudes above 100 km.&#160;\r\nTo-date, sRLV providers have not achieved flight to 100 km, but are\r\ntargeting to fly to that altitude by the end of calendar year 2011. In the\r\ninterim, pathfinder opportunities exist for responders to fly payloads below\r\n100 km utilizing the providers evolving commercial capabilities.\r\n\r\n</p><p>NASA will provide access to these platforms for different communities. Our primary focus is for technology maturation, as part of the pipeline currently being developed for the Office of the Chief Technologist.</p><p>In addition, opportunities for science and education are also available through the program.</p></div>'),(317,'<h5>Opportunities</h5>'),(251,'<div class=\"grid_6 alpha\"><h3>Parabolic Flights</h3>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"grid_3 alpha\"><h3>Fast turn around</h3><p>Duis enim purus, suscipit bibendum pellentesque ut, pharetra non nisl. Etiam urna lorem, pretium non cursus non, ornare sed sem. Curabitur quis sapien et ante hendrerit viverra aliquam vel lorem. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"grid_3 omega\"><h3>New environment</h3><p>Duis enim purus, suscipit bibendum pellentesque ut, pharetra non nisl. Etiam urna lorem, pretium non cursus non, ornare sed sem. Curabitur quis sapien et ante hendrerit viverra aliquam vel lorem. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<h3>Suborbital RLVs</h3>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"grid_3 alpha\"><h3>Fast turn around</h3><p>Duis enim purus, suscipit bibendum pellentesque ut, pharetra non nisl. Etiam urna lorem, pretium non cursus non, ornare sed sem. Curabitur quis sapien et ante hendrerit viverra aliquam vel lorem. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"grid_3 omega\"><h3>New environment</h3><p>Duis enim purus, suscipit bibendum pellentesque ut, pharetra non nisl. Etiam urna lorem, pretium non cursus non, ornare sed sem. Curabitur quis sapien et ante hendrerit viverra aliquam vel lorem. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"grid_3 alpha\"><h3>Build a little, fly a little</h3><p>Duis enim purus, suscipit bibendum pellentesque ut, pharetra non nisl. Etiam urna lorem, pretium non cursus non, ornare sed sem. Curabitur quis sapien et ante hendrerit viverra aliquam vel lorem. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n<div class=\"grid_3 omega\"><h3>Low cost</h3><p>Duis enim purus, suscipit bibendum pellentesque ut, pharetra non nisl. Etiam urna lorem, pretium non cursus non, ornare sed sem. Curabitur quis sapien et ante hendrerit viverra aliquam vel lorem. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>'),(253,'<div class=\"grid_6 omega\"><img src=\"/fop/media/cms/images/plugins/image.png\" alt=\"Picture - XPrizeFlightTrajectory.jpg\" title=\"Picture - XPrizeFlightTrajectory.jpg\" id=\"plugin_obj_161\" />\r\n</div>'),(257,'<h1>Features about science</h1><br />'),(277,'<div class=\"grid_6 alpha\"><p>Education is an important part of the Flight Opportunities Program mission. We are currently working through the details on how to enable the program for education payloads and programs. We will be working together with AERO institute who will look for education opportunities throughout the program.</p><h3>If you have ideas for education, please contact AERO Institute.</h3></div>'),(273,'<h2>Where to find funding for payload development?</h2><br />'),(337,'<p>To the greatest extent possible, the PM must maintain some insight into the technology pipelines across the Office of Chief Technologist (OCT), especially the Game Changing Development Program and within the Crosscutting Capability Demonstrations Division (CCDD).</p>'),(338,'<p>Dryden Flight Research Center (DFRC) is responsible and accountable for the management of the Flight Opportunities Program.  The Level II Program Manager resides at DFRC and works in collaboration with the NASA HQ Program Executive, who reports directly to the Cross Cutting Capabilities Division Director. Payload Management for Flight Opportunities is based at NASA Ames Research Center in Moffet Field, California.</p>'),(342,'<p>The Flight Opportunities Program develops and provides flight opportunities for Space Technologies to be demonstrated and validated in relevant environments. &#160;The Program is also a service provider to the technology initiatives, both inside and outside of the Office of Chief Technologist (OCT).  Technology pipelines are established through guided and competed selections.  \r\n\r\nTechnology partners come from wherever there are driving technology developments that align with the Space Technology Roadmap.&#160;These technology developments will happen internally through OCT initiatives and externally through leveraged partnerships.</p>\r\n'),(425,'<h2>Our principle customers are:</h2>'),(347,'<p>With cooperative efforts of the Flight Providers, the program will develop subsidiary industries.  Payload adapters are required to flybidize experiments.  With standardized payload equipment, safety evaluations and hardware integration will be streamlined.  Payload integrators will function to assess payload safety and the integration of multiple payloads onto a single vehicle (similar to TSA and baggage handlers at airports).\r\nThe goal is to have the Flight Providers to become Spacelines where they will operate like an airline, providing full flight services to include payload adaptations integration and flights.</p><p>\r\nPayload Operations Centers will be incorporated into the Spaceports to provide a facility for researchers to work with the Payload Integrators to prepare payloads for flights and to interact with the payloads during the flight.</p>'),(354,'<p><strong>Flight Opportunity Program</strong>:  provides flight opportunities for technology development to reduced-gravity environments, brief periods of weightlessness and high-altitude atmospheric research. </p><p><strong>Chief Technologist</strong>: serves as the NASA Administrators principal advisor and advocate on matters concerning agency-wide technology policy and programs. </p><p><strong>Office of the Chief Technologist</strong>: responsible for direct management of NASAs Space Technology programs and for coordination and tracking of all technology investments across the agency. </p><p><strong>Technology Readiness Level (TRL) Definitions: </strong></p><ul><li>TRL 9: Actual system \"flight proven\" through successful mission operations. </li><li>TRL 8: Actual system completed and \"flight qualified\" through test &amp; demonstration (ground or space). </li><li>TRL 7: System prototype demonstration in a space environment. </li><li>TRL 6: System/subsystem model or prototype demonstration in a relevant environment (ground or space). </li><li>TRL 5: Component and/or breadboard validation in relevant environment. </li><li>TRL 4: Component and/or breadboard validation in laboratory environment. </li><li>TRL 3: Analytical and experimental critical function and/or characteristic proof-of-concept. </li><li>TRL 2: Technology concept and/or application formulated. </li><li>TRL 1: Basic principles observed and reported.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n \r\n<p><strong>Flybidize</strong>:  the transformation of an experiment into a payload that meets the volumetric, environmental, and operational constraints of the flight vehicle. </p><p><strong>Suborbital Rocket</strong>: a vehicle, rocket-propelled in whole or in part, intended for flight on a suborbital trajectory, and the thrust of which is greater than its lift for the majority of the rocket-powered portion of its ascent. </p><p><strong>Suborbital Trajectory</strong>: the intentional flight path of a launch vehicle, reentry vehicle, or any portion thereof, whose vacuum instantaneous impact point does not leave the surface of the Earth. </p><p><strong>Key Decision Point (KDP)</strong>:  the event at which the Decision Authority determines the readiness of a program/project to progress to the next phase of the life cycle (or to the next KDP). </p><p><strong>Guided technology</strong>:  technology that meet high value strategic goals and critical needs</p><p><strong>Proof of Concept</strong>:  Analytical and experimental demonstration of hardware/software concepts that may or may not be incorporated into subsequent development and/or operational units. </p><p><strong>Breadboard</strong>: A low fidelity unit that demonstrates function only, without respect to form or fit in the case of hardware, or platform in the case of software. It often uses commercial and/or ad hoc components and is not intended to provide definitive information regarding operational performance. </p><p><strong>Brassboard</strong>:  A medium fidelity functional unit that typically tries to make use of as much operational hardware/software as possible and begins to address scaling issues associated with the operational system. It does not have the engineering pedigree in all aspects, but is structured to be able to operate in simulated operational environments in order to assess performance of critical functions. </p><p><strong>Proto-type Unit</strong>:  The proto-type unit demonstrates form, fit, and function at a scale deemed to be representative of the final product operating in its operational environment. A subscale test article provides fidelity sufficient to permit validation of analytical models capable of predicting the behavior of full-scale systems in an operational environment </p><p><strong>Engineering Unit</strong>:  A high fidelity unit that demonstrates critical aspects of the engineering processes involved in the development of the operational unit. Engineering test units are intended to closely resemble the final product (hardware/software) to the maximum extent possible and are built and tested so as to establish confidence that the design will function in the expected environments. In some cases, the engineering unit will become the final product, assuming proper traceability has been exercised over the components and hardware handling. </p><p><strong>Mission Configuration</strong>:  The final architecture/system design of the product that will be used in the operational environment. If the product is a subsystem/component, then it is embedded in the actual system in the actual configuration used in operation. </p><p><strong>Laboratory Environment:</strong>  An environment that does not address in any manner the environment to be encountered by the system, subsystem, or component (hardware or software) during its intended operation. Tests in a laboratory environment are solely for the purpose of demonstrating the underlying principles of technical performance (functions), without respect to the impact of environment. </p><p><strong>Relevant Environment</strong>:  Not all systems, subsystems, and/or components need to be operated in the operational environment in order to satisfactorily address performance margin requirements. Consequently, the relevant environment is the specific subset of the operational environment that is required to demonstrate critical \"at risk\" aspects of the final product performance in an operational environment. It is an environment that focuses specifically on \"stressing\" the technology advance in question. </p><p><strong>Operational Environment</strong>:  The environment in which the final product will be operated. In the case of space flight hardware/software, it is space. In the case of ground-based or airborne systems that are not directed toward space flight, it will be the environments defined by the scope of operations. For software, the environment will be defined by the operational platform.</p>\r\n\r\n'),(376,'<p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">VIDEO</p>'),(378,'<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<p class=\"flightdate-value\">-</p>\r\n<p class=\"flightdate\">EXPECTED COMMERCIAL OPERATIONS</p>\r\n<p class=\"flightdate-value\">2012</p>\r\n<p class=\"flightdate\">EXPECTED FIRST TEST FLIGHTS</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\" style=\"font-size: 15px;\">Mark II [Mark I]</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">KEY SPECIFICATIONS</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">HTHL / Piloted</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPE</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">1 passenger / 1 pilot</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">PASSENGERS</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">110 km [61 km]</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MAXIMUM ALTITUDE</p>	\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">30-45 minutes</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPICAL FLIGHT DURATION</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">186 sec [56 sec]</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPICAL DURATION OF MICROGRAVITY</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">less than 0.01 g</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MICROGRAVITY LEVEL</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">140 kg internal [140 kg]</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">&gt;650 kg external [280 kg]</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">USEFUL PAYLOAD MASS</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">+/- 0.5 deg [+/- 2 deg]</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">POINTING ACCURACY</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">28 VDC</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">POWER</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">9.6 kbit/sec TM/TC (phoneline rate)</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TELEMETRY</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">Mojave Air and Space Port, CA</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">INITIAL SPACEPORT</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Access to external environment</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Data storage provided</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Reduced gravity capability</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> FASTRACK compatible</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Windowed access to the outside</p>\r\n<br /><br />\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><a href=\"/media/uploads/xcor-nasa-crusr-rfi-response-mod2.pdf\">Public RFI response [pdf] </a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MORE INFORMATION</p>\r\n</div>\r\n		\r\n<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<h3>XCOR Aerospace</h3>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">1314 Flightline<br />Mojave, CA 93502</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">OFFICE</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">Andrew Nelson<br />Cell: (617) 899-8873<br />Email: <a href=\"mailto:anelson@xcor.com\">anelson@xcor.com</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">POINT OF CONTACT</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><a href=\"http://www.xcor.com/\">www.xcor.com </a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">WEBSITE</p>\r\n</div>\r\n		\r\n<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<h3>Resources</h3>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><a href=\"http://www.xcor.com/products/vehicles/lynx_suborbital.html\">Lynx on www.xcor.com </a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lynx_rocketplane\">Lynx on Wikipedia </a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><a href=\"http://www.youtube.com/user/XCORAerospace\">XCOR on Youtube </a></p>\r\n</div>'),(379,'<h1>New Shepard</h1>\r\n<h5>Blue Origin</h5>'),(380,'<p class=\"image-caption\">Prototype \'Goddard\' vehicle (2006). Credit: Blue Origin</p>'),(381,'<br /><p style=\"font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 0px; font-weight: bold; color: rgb(115, 2, 9);\">DISCLAIMER</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: rgb(115, 2, 9);\">The data on this page was provided by the respondent in answer to a NASA Request for Information (RFI). The vendor\'s RFI response is provided as-is.\r\nNASA cannot verify the claims made in the vendor RFI response. Please contact the vendor for the most current information.</p>'),(382,'<p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">PLATFORM</p>\r\n<p>The <em>New Shepard</em> system is comprised of a Propulsion Module and a Crew Capsule, the latter being stacked on top of the Propulsion Module, and capable of separating from the Propulsion Module during flight.</p><p>Flight testing of a prototype <em>New Shepard</em> system began in 2006. Blue Origin expects the first opportunities for experiments requiring an accompanying researcher astronaut to be available in 2012. Flight opportunities in 2011 may be available for autonomous or remotely-controlled experiments on an uncrewed flight test.</p><p><em>Note that the image above depicts the prototype \'Goddard\' test vehicle during a testflight in 2006, not the <em>New Shepard</em> system.</em></p>'),(383,'<p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">FLIGHT PROFILE</p>\r\n<p>The <em>New Shepard</em> system launches vertically, ascends to suborbital altitudes over 100 km and performs a powered vertical landing for recovery and reuse of the vehicle. The <em>New Shepard</em> system launch, flight and landing activities take approximately 10 minutes. Blue Origin anticipates that the Crew Capsule will experience 3 or more minutes of microgravity at a level less than 0.001 g during a typical flight.</p>'),(384,'<p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">PAYLOAD CONFIGURATION</p>\r\n<p>Experiments will be hosted inside the Crew Capsule in standard Cabin Payload System (CPS) racks. Each rack supports a total of 10.6 cubic feet (over 300 liters) of available volume divided in standard Cabin Payload Bays (CPBs) of either 1.8 cubic feet (over 50 liters) or double-height 3.6 cubic feet (over 100 liters). </p><p>The Crew Capsule will contain windows, allowing viewing of both Earth and space. Experiment racks could be positioned to optimize window access and field of view. Blue Origin is exploring the possibility of supporting externally-mounted experiments, such as sensors that can sample the atmosphere. These experiments will likely be constrained not to violate the outer mold line of the vehicle.</p><p>See the <a href=\"/media/uploads/blueorigin-nasa-crusr-rfi-response-mod2.pdf\">public RFI response</a> for more details.</p>'),(385,'<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<h3 class=\"flightdate-value\">-</h3>\r\n<p class=\"flightdate\">EXPECTED COMMERCIAL OPERATIONS</p>\r\n<h3 class=\"flightdate-value\">2011</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-size: 12px;\">EXPECTED FIRST TEST FLIGHTS</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\" style=\"font-size: 15px;\">New Shepard</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">KEY SPECIFICATIONS</p>\r\n\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">VTVL / Unpiloted</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPE</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">3 or more</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">ON-BOARD RESEARCHER ASTRONAUTS</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">100 km</p>\r\n\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">MAXIMUM ALTITUDE</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">~10 minutes</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPICAL FLIGHT DURATION</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">~ 3 or more minutes</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPICAL DURATION OF MICROGRAVITY</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">less than 0.001 g</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">MICROGRAVITY LEVEL</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">11.3 kg standard Cabin Payload Bay<br />22.7 kg for double-height CPB</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">USEFUL PAYLOAD MASS</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">+/- 5 deg during coast (&lt; 0.5 deg/s)</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">POINTING ACCURACY</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">28 VDC</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">POWER</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">1Mbps</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">TELEMETRY</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">West Texas Launch Site (WTLS), Culberson County, TX</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec\">INITIAL SPACEPORT</p>\r\n <p class=\"platform-spec-value\">Under investigation</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">ACCESS TO EXTERNAL ENVIRONMENT</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Data storage provided (&gt;250 Gb)</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Reduced gravity capability</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\" style=\"margin:0 0 10px 20px;\"> (BY SPECIAL ARRANGEMENT)</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> FASTRACK compatible</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Windowed access to the outside</p>\r\n<br /><br />\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><a href=\"/media/uploads/blueorigin-nasa-crusr-rfi-response-mod2.pdf\">Public RFI response [pdf] </a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MORE INFORMATION</p>\r\n</div>\r\n		\r\n<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<h3>Blue Origin LLC</h3>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">21218 76th Avenue S.<br />Kent, WA 98032</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">OFFICE</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">West Texas Launch Site<br />Culberson County, TX</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">R&amp;D AND LAUNCH LOCATION</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">Dr. Alan Stern<br />Office: (303) 324-5269<br />Email: <a href=\"mailto:astern@blueorigin.com\">astern@blueorigin.com</a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">POINT OF CONTACT</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><a href=\"http://www.blueorigin.com/\">www.blueorigin.com </a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">WEBSITE</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<h3>Resources</h3>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">\r\n<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Origin\">Blue Origin on Wikipedia </a><br />\r\n</p>\r\n</div>'),(387,'<h1>SpaceShipTwo</h1>\r\n<h5>Virgin Galactic</h5>'),(388,'<p class=\"image-caption\">SpaceShipTwo VSS Enterprise (October 2010). Credit: Mark Greenberg</p>'),(390,'<br /><p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">PLATFORM</p>\r\n<p>SpaceShipTwo (SS2) uses all the same basic technology, carbon composite construction and design as SpaceShipOne (SS1). However it is around twice as large as that vehicle and will carry six passengers and two pilots. It is 18.3 m (60 ft) long with a 2.28 m (90\") diameter cabin which is similar in size to a Falcon 900 executive jet albeit with no floor dissecting the cabin allowing maximum room for the astronauts to float in zero gravity.</p>'),(391,'<p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">FLIGHT PROFILE</p>\r\n<p>SpaceShipTwo is carried to its launch altitude of approximately 15 km (approx. 45,000 ft) by the purpose-built carrier aircraft WhiteKnightTwo (WK2). This climb up to altitude takes around an hour. SpaceShipTwo is subsequently air-launched from the carrier and fires its rocket motor, executing a turn for a steep climb which lasts ~70 seconds before the motor shuts down. SpaceShipTwo then follows a typical ballistic arc and deploys its \'feathered\' configuration for re-entry. Following ~70 seconds of re-entry and descent into the atmosphere, SS2 de-feathers and glides to a horizontal landing at its launch base.</p>'),(392,'<p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">PAYLOAD CONFIGURATION</p>\r\n<p>SpaceShipTwo will have a baseline seat for tourism operations and baseline rack for individual (direct passenger replacement) payloads. Different payloads and racks can be accomodated and both the system and operations are flexible in both payload and mission profile. Experiments can also be mounted in unpressurized bays of SpaceShipTwo for research requiring direct access to the space environment, e.g. atmospheric sampling or exposure to the external spaceflight environment.</p><p style=\"color: rgb(141, 4, 12);\">PLEASE TAKE NOTE: NASA is presently not considering human-tended payloads to be flown on sRLVs and there will not be any NASA-sponsored participants on sRLV flights. The payloads to be flown on sRLV flights must either be automated or remotely operated. Remote operation capability should be confirmed with the flight operator.</p><p>See the <a href=\"http://www.virgingalactic.com/uploads/VG_Web_PayloadUsersGuide_20111206.pdf\">Payload Users Guide (Dec 2011)</a> for more information. For questions about the SpaceShipTwo platform, please <a href=\"http://www.virgingalactic.com/news/item/conducting-research-on-spaceshiptwo-and-whiteknighttwo/\">contact Virgin Galactic</a>.</p>'),(397,'<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<h3 class=\"flightdate-value\">2013 (Expected)</h3>\r\n<p style=\"font-size: 12px; margin-bottom: 20px;\">COMMERCIAL OPERATIONS</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\" style=\"font-size: 15px;\">SpaceShipTwo</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">KEY SPECIFICATIONS</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">HTHL / Piloted</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPE</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">6 passengers / 2 pilots</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">PASSENGERS</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">110 km</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MAXIMUM ALTITUDE</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">~90 minutes</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPICAL FLIGHT DURATION</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">~4 minutes</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPICAL DURATION OF MICROGRAVITY</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">tbd</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MICROGRAVITY LEVEL</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">tbd</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">USEFUL PAYLOAD MASS</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">tbd</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">POINTING ACCURACY</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">tbd</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">POWER</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">tbd</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">DATA STORAGE PROVIDED</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">Spaceport America, NM</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-size: 11px; margin-bottom: 20px;\">INITIAL SPACEPORT</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Access to external environment</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"cross\"></span> Telemetry</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Reduced gravity capability</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> FASTRACK compatible</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Windowed access to the outside</p>\r\n<br /><br />\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><a href=\"http://www.virgingalactic.com/research\">Payload Users Guide Dec 2011 </a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MORE INFORMATION</p>\r\n</div>'),(495,'<p>Each of the sRLV platforms listed here is or will possibly become available \r\nfor researchers to fly payloads on. At present, these platforms are \r\neither operational, presently undergoing test flights or will likely become \r\navailable for initial test flights during the 2011-2012-2013 timeframe. The \r\nsRLVs that are being developed by companies in this industry have \r\ndifferent capabilities, and responders are encouraged to investigate the\r\n different options.</p><p style=\"color: red;\">The comparison presented here is based on information provided by the Flight Providers to NASA&#160;in May 2010&#160;as part of a public response to a Request for Information (RFI). The public RFI responses are linked to in the comparison table and on each individual platform detail page. An indepth overview of specifications abstracted from the public RFI submissions is available as pdf:</p>'),(906,'<p>This vehicle has been phased out by its supplier. Please refer to other vehicles currently on offer through the Flight Opportunities Program.</p>'),(907,'<h1>SuperMod</h1>\r\n<h5>Armadillo Aerospace</h5>'),(409,'<h1>Xaero</h1>\r\n<h5>Masten Space Systems</h5>'),(412,'<br /><p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">PLATFORM</p>\r\n<p>Xaero is a reconfiguration from the Xoie platform that won Level II of the Lunar Lander Challenge. The company expects Xaero to begin higher altitude and higher speed flights in the fourth quarter of 2011. Xaero is expected to be able to carry a 10 kg payload to approximately 30 kilometers (or 100,000 feet) according to current models with higher masses at lower altitudes or shorter flight durations.</p>'),(413,'<p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">FLIGHT PROFILE</p>\r\n<p>Xaero takes off and land vertically in the same place it launches from. The flight profile consists of launch, acceleration to Mach 0.9 throughout the majority of atmospheric resistance, then going full throttle before shutting off the engine.</p><p>During parabolic coast phase the payload experiences microgravity. As the vehicle descends back into the atmosphere and gains speed the coast phase ends. At this point the rocket stabilizes itself and falls towards the ground engine-first before the engine re-lights and lands the vehicle on the same pad used for takeoff.</p><p>Flight profiles have some flexibility for payload specific needs and are assessed on a per payload basis. Flight profiles on all vehicles can be modified for lower accelerations with minimal loss of altitude and microgravity time.</p>'),(414,'<p style=\"font-size:15px; margin-bottom:0px;font-weight:bold\">PAYLOAD CONFIGURATION</p>\r\n<p>Xaero is the companys first vehicle to use an aeroshell. Xaero and Xogdor (next generation platform) use the same basic aeroshell and payload bay design. The upper payload bay is roughly conical.</p><p>Payload placement slots are available in both the forward section of the nose cone or in smaller areas toward the aft end of the vehicle. As currently designed, Xaero\'s airframe allows for P-POD Cubesat carriers and single ESPA ring mounts as a standard payload format. Lower bays are limited in size and do not adhere to any existing payload interface standard.</p><p>See the <a href=\"http://masten-space.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/MSS-payload-guide-2011-1.2.4OSR.pdf\">Xaero Payload User\'s Guide (December 2011)</a> for more details. Please contact Colin Ake at <a href=\"mailto:cake@masten-space.com\">cake@masten-space.com</a> or 678.551.2253 for more information.</p>'),(418,'<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<h3 class=\"flightdate-value\">2012 (Expected)</h3>\r\n<p class=\"flightdate\">COMMERCIAL OPERATIONS</p>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"topbox\">\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\" style=\"font-size: 15px;\">Xaero</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">KEY SPECIFICATIONS</p>\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">VTVL / Unpiloted</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPE</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">n/a</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">PASSENGERS</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">30 km</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MAXIMUM ALTITUDE</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">5-6 minutes at 30 km (100,000 ft)</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPICAL FLIGHT DURATION</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">12.5 sec (10 kg)<br />5.1 sec (40 kg)</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">TYPICAL DURATION OF MICROGRAVITY</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"> &lt;0.001 g</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MICROGRAVITY LEVEL</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">10 kg</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">USEFUL PAYLOAD MASS AT 30 KM</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">+/- 2.5 deg during coast</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">POINTING ACCURACY</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">12VDC or 24VDC</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">POWER</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\">Mojave Air and Space Port, CA</p>\r\n<p style=\"font-size: 11px; margin-bottom: 20px;\">INITIAL SPACEPORT</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Access to external environment</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"cross\"></span> Telemetry (is coming)</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"cross\"></span> Data storage provided</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Reduced gravity capability</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"cross\"></span> FASTRACK compatible</p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><span class=\"checkmark\"></span> Windowed access to the outside</p>\r\n<br /><br />\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec-value\"><a href=\"http://masten-space.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/MSS-payload-guide-2011-1.2.4OSR.pdf\">Payload User\'s Guide (Dec 2011) </a></p>\r\n<p class=\"platform-spec\">MORE INFORMATION</p>\r\n</div>\r\n	\r\n	'),(422,'<h2>Definitions</h2>'),(481,'<div class=\"grid_8 alpha\"><h2>Want to fly your technology?</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The Announcement of Flight Opportunities (AFO) is open until the end of December, 2014. To learn more about how to submit your proposal, find our Announcement of Flight Opportunities (AFO) on NSPIRES:&#160;</p><p><a class=\"big_link\" href=\"http://nspires.nasaprs.com/external/solicitations/summary.do?method=init&amp;solId=%7B0A6C5D60-20F3-E7FE-D4A3-710AE8AA43B6%7D&amp;path=open\">Announcement of Flight Opportunities (AFO) </a>\r\n</p>\r\n<p>Interested to learn more? Shoot us an <a href=\"mailto:nasa-flightopportunities@mail.nasa.gov\">email</a> and we\'ll get back to you! Also don\'t forget to <a href=\"https://lists.nasa.gov/mailman/listinfo/flightopportunities-news\">subscribe to our mailing list</a> and <a href=\"http://twitter.com/nasafo\">follow us on Twitter</a> for community updates and announcements of future flight opportunities.</p>\r\n</div>'),(484,'<h1>sRLV platforms compared</h1>'),(487,'<style>\r\n\r\n.compare table {\r\n    table-layout: fixed;\r\n}\r\n\r\n.table .tr .th. .table .tbody {\r\n    background: none repeat scroll 0 0 #FFFFFF;\r\n    padding: 5px 20px;\r\n    vertical-align: top;\r\n    width: 188px;\r\n}\r\n\r\n.compare th, .compare .th, .compare td, .compare .td {\r\n    background: none repeat scroll 0 0 #FFFFFF;\r\n    padding: 5px 10px;\r\n    vertical-align: top;\r\n    width: 188px;\r\n}\r\n.table .tr {\r\n    border-left: 1px solid #E8E8E8;\r\n}\r\n\r\n.compare .column0, .compare .column0 {\r\n    border: medium none;\r\n}\r\n\r\n.compare th, .compare .th {\r\n    color: #000000;\r\n    font-size: 12px;\r\n    font-weight: bold;\r\n}\